courier (1.1.10) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Local cache now serves `read`, `links`, and `attachments` from
    disk for any [imap.NAME] with `maildir` configured; previously
    only `search` consulted the cache and the other paths
    round-tripped to IMAP unconditionally. Read of a known UID
    serves from disk in ~0.6 s with zero IMAP traffic.
  * The redact policy no longer disables the local cache. The
    eligibility check that bypassed the cache whenever a
    `redact = "rules.sieve"` field was set is removed; the policy
    is now applied on the local hits as well, so compound queries
    against a redact-bearing block serve from cache in ~5 s
    instead of ~16 s, and the maildir path is dropped from
    redacted records to close that leakage.
  * Warnings from `courier.imap_client` (search-folder timeouts,
    connection-verification failures, IMAP logout errors) are
    routed through syslog. On systemd hosts the records are
    queryable via `journalctl -t courier`; on platforms with no
    reachable syslog socket the existing stderr handler stays in
    place. Closes #39.
  * When `search` falls through to iterating every selectable
    folder, a WARNING now names the host, the size of the cached
    folder list, and the universe of LIST attribute flags seen,
    so the cause behind intermittent INBOX-only result sets can
    be attributed from journald without a live reproduction.
    Refs #38.
  * Documentation: sync-tool examples are no longer co-equal
    "offlineimap or mbsync"; offlineimap is named as one example
    of a maildir-producing tool. Fixes #37.

 -- Weiwu Zhang <a@colourful.land>  Wed, 13 May 2026 13:00:00 +0000

courier (1.1.9) unstable; urgency=medium

  * `-i` is now `--identity`, used by `compose`, `reply`, and
    `send-draft`. The previous 1.1.8 assignment of `-i` to
    `save --identifier` did not match the user-facing intent and
    is reverted.
  * `save --identifier` is renamed to `save --attachment` and has
    no short form. "identifier" was ambiguous against the project's
    other identifier-shaped fields (identity name, imap block name,
    smtp block name, message-id, uid). `--attachment` says exactly
    what it picks. Migration: `courier save -f INBOX -u 100
    -i Billete.pdf -o out.pdf` → `courier save -f INBOX -u 100
    --attachment Billete.pdf -o out.pdf`.
  * `--imap` remains the only spelling for the global IMAP-block
    selector; no short form.

 -- Weiwu Zhang <a@colourful.land>  Sun, 10 May 2026 13:00:00 +0000

courier (1.1.8) unstable; urgency=medium

  * `-i` is no longer a shorthand for `--imap`. Use `--imap NAME`
    at the top level. `-i` is now exclusively `save --identifier`
    (closes #36): previously `courier -i acct save -f INBOX -u 100
    -i "Billete.pdf" -o out.pdf` failed because the argv
    preprocessor consumed `save -i "Billete.pdf"` as a second
    `--imap`. Removing the shorthand removes the collision at the
    source. Migration: `courier -i NAME ...` →
    `courier --imap NAME ...`.
  * `-n/--limit` and `-f/--folder` are now chain-level: a trailing
    `-n N` or `-f FOLDER` after the last verb applies to every
    chained verb that doesn't set its own value (closes #34). So
    `courier search a search b -f INBOX -n 5` runs both searches
    against INBOX with limit 5 instead of leaving the trailing
    flags attached to the last verb.
  * MCP tool coverage: `search_emails`, `read`, and `folders` are
    consistently exposed; thread matching uses strict-subject
    semantics (closes #11).
  * `install-claude-command` is now version-aware. It checks the
    installed `courier.md` against the bundled one and prompts
    before overwriting; the `--force` flag is removed. The status
    nudge surfaces globally when registration is missing.

 -- Weiwu Zhang <a@colourful.land>  Sun, 10 May 2026 12:00:00 +0000

courier (1.1.7) unstable; urgency=medium

  * `search` and `read` repeat at the top level to run several
    operations in one invocation:
        courier -A search "sergio" search "panedas" read -f INBOX -u 42
    Each operation gets its own outer key in the result, so per-keyword
    hit attribution is preserved. Output is JSON of shape
    `{op_key: {imap_name: result}}`, the same shape single-op `search`
    and `read` already produced.
  * The `batch` subcommand is removed. Anyone driving courier from a
    script that ran `courier batch "search foo" "search bar"` should
    switch to `courier search foo search bar`. The output shape is
    unchanged. Issue #34 tracks promoting `--limit` and `--folder` to
    chain-level so they apply to every chained verb.

 -- Weiwu Zhang <a@colourful.land>  Wed, 06 May 2026 12:00:00 +0000

courier (1.1.6) unstable; urgency=medium

  * New `install-claude-command` subcommand: copies the bundled
    Claude Code command file into ~/.claude/commands/courier.md so
    Claude Code recognises courier and routes email-related prompts
    through the CLI. The file ships inside the Python package, so
    the same one-liner works regardless of install method.
    `courier status` notes when ~/.claude exists but courier is
    not yet registered.
  * Plain-text bodies containing markdown tables or headings now
    auto-render an HTML alternative on send. The wire form goes as
    multipart/alternative with the original plain text as the first
    part and rendered HTML as the second, so recipients see tables
    and structure while plain-text-only clients still get the
    intended source. Closes #28.

 -- Weiwu Zhang <a@colourful.land>  Wed, 06 May 2026 00:00:00 +0000

courier (1.1.5) unstable; urgency=medium

  * `courier status` is now a connection-probe table rather than a
    JSON inventory. Every [imap.NAME] runs a full IMAP login attempt
    and every [smtp.NAME] runs an EHLO + STARTTLS handshake plus an
    authenticated login when the block carries credentials. Output
    is a short aligned table answering "which servers are reachable
    right now". Probes run concurrently across blocks. Template SMTP
    blocks (no own creds, inherit at send time) are probed as far as
    STARTTLS only and marked accordingly. Scripts that parsed the
    prior status JSON inventory should switch to `courier list`,
    which still emits it. Closes #29.

 -- Weiwu Zhang <a@colourful.land>  Wed, 06 May 2026 00:00:00 +0000

courier (1.1.4) unstable; urgency=medium

  * New per-account redact policy. An optional `redact = "rules.sieve"`
    field on `[imap.NAME]` points at a Sieve script; messages matching
    any rule are replaced with a placeholder Email before reaching the
    agent or the third-party model provider. The placeholder preserves
    UID, date, folder and threading headers so the agent knows the
    message exists and can reason about timing, but cannot read the
    parties, the subject, or the body. Two motivating cases:

    1. Keep privileged correspondence (legal counsel, HR, medical) out
       of the agent's view and out of model-provider logs while the
       containing mailbox stays connected for everything else.

    2. Restrict the agent to a defined scope inside a shared mailbox,
       e.g. an account that mixes work and personal mail can hide the
       personal correspondence from a work-context agent.

    Supported Sieve subset: `address` and `header` tests with `:is`,
    `:contains`, and `:matches` (leading/trailing glob); `anyof`,
    `allof`, `not` combinators; one custom action `redact;` declared
    by `require ["courier-policy"];`. Out-of-subset constructs fail
    closed at config-load time. Sample script in
    /usr/share/doc/courier/examples/work-only.sieve.
  * New runtime dependency on python3-sievelib for the redact policy
    parser. Accounts that do not configure `redact` are unaffected.

 -- Weiwu Zhang <a@colourful.land>  Tue, 06 May 2026 00:00:00 +0000

courier (1.1.3) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Refuse to send when no copy of the message will be retained. A send
    is allowed only if FCC will run, or the BCC list includes the
    sender's own address. A BCC addressed only to a third party is no
    longer treated as a self-copy. Pass --allow-no-copy on
    compose/reply/send-draft to override.
  * New `bcc` field on `[identity.NAME]` (string or list of strings):
    addresses appended to BCC on every send from this identity, useful
    for self-archiving via mail rules. With `bcc` set, the `imap` field
    becomes optional; a send-only identity that BCCs itself needs no
    IMAP block in scope.
  * Homebrew formula on macOS Tahoe now depends on `expat` and wraps
    the entry point with DYLD_LIBRARY_PATH so pyexpat resolves against
    Homebrew's expat instead of the older system library (#26).

 -- Weiwu Zhang <a@colourful.land>  Mon, 04 May 2026 00:00:00 +0000

courier (1.1.2) unstable; urgency=medium

  * compose/reply/send-draft --send now require an explicit route. Either
    --identity NAME (mode A: resolves From, display name, IMAP block,
    SMTP, sent_folder from a configured [identity.NAME]), or
    --smtp NAME --from EMAIL (mode B: sends a free-form From through a
    named SMTP block without consulting [identity.*]). Closes the
    silent-default hazard from #25 where omitting the route would pick
    the first identity on the resolved [imap.NAME] block.
  * Mode B accepts optional --name (validated against the same rules as
    [identity.*] name) and --fcc IMAP_NAME:FOLDER (appends a copy on
    success; without --fcc no copy is saved). The SMTP block must carry
    its own username/password in mode B, since no [imap.*] is in scope
    for credential inheritance.
  * reply --send: when neither flag is given, courier matches the
    parent's recipients against identities; if no recipient matches, the
    command errors rather than silently picking identities[0]. Drafting
    keeps the previous fallback behaviour.
  * Drafting (no --send) is unchanged: --imap selects the block, the
    block's first identity is the From by default, --from selects a
    different identity by address.

 -- Weiwu Zhang <a@colourful.land>  Sun, 03 May 2026 00:00:00 +0000

courier (1.1.1) unstable; urgency=medium

  * SMTP send capability: --send flag on compose and reply transmits via
    SMTP instead of saving to drafts; new send-draft subcommand reads a
    draft from IMAP and transmits it.
  * New [smtp.NAME] config blocks declare named SMTP endpoints; per-account
    default_smtp routes outgoing mail; [[identities]] tables enable send-as
    with one mailbox handling multiple From addresses.
  * Captures the post-DATA SMTP response and rewrites Message-ID to the
    recipient-visible form when the smarthost issues one (e.g. SES).
  * After a successful send, FCCs (IMAP-APPENDs) the wire-form bytes to the
    identity's Sent folder, with Bcc stripped and Message-ID rewritten.
  * New config-check subcommand validates cross-references and identity
    resolution without performing IMAP or SMTP traffic; the same warnings
    surface on `courier`, `--help`, `status`, and `list-accounts`.

